d Kingdom","Belleswarden, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Harnage","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Harnage in Shropshire, which has as its second element Old English <i>ecg</i> ‘edge, steep ridge’; the first is uncertain but may be a derivative, <i>hæren</i> ‘rocky’, of an unrecorded Old English <i>hær</i> ‘stone’. The surname now appears to be extinct in England; in the US it is concentrated in FL and GA."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jane","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jayne","meanings":["Elaborated spelling of   Jane  , a form popularized no doubt by the American actress  Jayne Mansfield  (  Vera Jayne Palmer ,  1933–67 ) and British ice-dancer  Jayne Torvill  (  b. 1957 )."]},{"name":"Jaine","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jane ."]},{"name":"Jain","meanings":["Originally a feminine form of   John  , from the Old French form <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Since the 17th century it has proved the most popular of the feminine forms of <i>John</i>, ahead of   Joan   and   Jean .  It now also commonly occurs as the second element in combinations such as <i>Sarah-Jane</i>. In Britain it is still one of the most frequent of all girls' names. It is not a royal name, but was borne by the tragic  Lady Jane Grey  (  1537–54 ), who was unwillingly proclaimed queen in  1553 , deposed nine days later, and executed the following year. Seventy years earlier, the name had come into prominence as that of  Jane Shore , mistress of  King Edward IV  and subsequently of  Thomas Grey , 1st Marquess of Dorset, Lady Jane's grandfather. Jane Shore's tribulations in  1483  at the hands of  Richard III , Edward's brother and successor, became the subject of popular ballads and plays, which may well have increased the currency of the name in the 16th century. A 19th-century influence was its use as the name of the central character in  Charlotte Brontë's  novel Jane Eyre (  1847 ). From  1932 to 1959  it was used as the name of a cheerful and scantily clad beauty whose adventures were chronicled in a strip cartoon in the Daily Mirror. It is also borne by the American film stars  Jane Russell  (  1921–2011 ) and  Jane Fonda  (  b. 1937 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Jane Harnage was born about 1412, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Joseph de Harnage of Belleswarden, was 14 and her mother, Harriet Shugart, was 10. She married Sir William Poyner of Bedeslow about 1434, in Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1443, in Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 32."},"et":{"Abt 1412–1443":"umbes 1412–1443","1412–1443":"1412–1443","1423–1445":"1423–1445","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1443–1462":"1443–1462","1399–1424":"1399–1424","1403–1424":"1403–1424","1403":"1403","1424":"1424","1402":"1402","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1443":"1443","1399":"1399","1462":"1462","about 1434":"umbes 1434","Abt 1412":"umbes 1412","Bedeslow, Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Jarrow, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham Castle,Durham,England.":"Durham, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bedeslow, Shropshire, England.":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Jarrow, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Durham,Durham,England,United Kingdom":"Durham, Durham, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Belleswarden, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1412–1443":"noin 1412–1443","1412–1443":"1412–1443","1423–1445":"1423–1445","1402–Male":"1402–Kuollut","1443–1462":"1443–1462","1399–1424":"1399–1424","1403–1424":"1403–1424","1403":"1403","1424":"1424","1402":"1402","1423":"1423","1445":"1445","1412":"1412","1443":"1443","1399":"1399","1462":"1462","about 1434":"noin 1434","Abt 1412":"noin 1412","Bedeslow, Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Jarrow, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Durham Castle,Durham,England.":"Durham, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bedeslow, Shropshire, England.":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Jarrow, Durham, England, United Kingdom":"Jarrow, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Durham,Durham,England,United Kingdom":"Durham, Durham, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Belleswarden, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Shropshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"